<DOC><DOCNO> AP890707-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 1808EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0476</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0495</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD><BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Visions of renewed declines in interest ratesprovided the inspiration for a broad advance in the stock marketFriday.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.42 points to2,487.86, stretching its advance for a holiday-shortened week offour consecutive gains to 47.80 points.   Issues rising in price outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 innationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with1,064 up, 472 down and 458 unchanged.   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 166.43 millionshares, up from 140.45 million in the previous session. Nationwide,consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in thosestocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,totaled 195.24 million shares.   The market opened on a hesitant note, but then picked up steam atmidsession as traders concluded that the Labor Department'semployment report for June had apparently encouraged the FederalReserve to relax its credit policy.   The report showed an increase of 180,000 in nonfarm payrollemployment, below most advance estimates.   The figures for May were revised to show a gain of 207,000, morethan double the 101,000 originally reported a month ago. Still,brokers said, Wall Streeters came increasingly to believe that theFed interpreted the data as reason enough to ease up on its creditrestraints.   Interest rates fell in the credit markets. Prices of long-termTreasury bonds rose more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value,reducing their yields to the 8.03 percent-8.06 percent range.   That helped fuel speculation that major banks might soon announcenew reductions in their prime lending rates.   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone andamp;Telegraph, up { at 35~; Coca-Cola, up 1{ at 58]; Philip Morris, up |at 141[; General Electric, up 1 at 53|, and International BusinessMachines, up { at 112[.   An exception was General Motors, down } at 40[ on word of newcutbacks in the company's production plans for the third quarter.   Honeywell climbed 4| to 77} on takeover speculation fueled by acolumn in Business Week magazine.   UAL, also buffeted by continuing takeover rumors, jumped 13{ to166. Among other leading airline issues, Delta Air Lines gained 1~to 72 and AMR was up \ at 64\.   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000actively traded stocks, the market increased $30.43 billion, or 0.96percent, in value.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained1.74 to 181.56.   Standard andamp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.68 to 370.87, and Sandamp;P's500-stock composite index was up 3.36 at 324.91.   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added2.85 to 442.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex closed at 363.75, up 2.64.</TEXT></DOC>